; mail-heavy.test
;
; A mail-centric zone. Demonstrates several MX with
; different preferences (clients try lowest first, fall
; back as needed), and the three TXT records that real
; mail systems publish for anti-spam / anti-spoofing:
; SPF declares which hosts are allowed to originate mail
; for this domain, DKIM publishes the public half of the
; signing key clients use to verify message integrity,
; and DMARC tells receivers what to do when SPF or DKIM
; fail.
;
; Try this in the demo: query mail-heavy.test for MX,
; then for TXT, then query the dkim selector
; (default._domainkey.mail-heavy.test) for TXT.
;
$ORIGIN mail-heavy.test.
$TTL 3600
@               IN  SOA   ns1.mail-heavy.test. postmaster.mail-heavy.test. (
                          2026010101 3600 1800 604800 86400 )
@               IN  NS    ns1.mail-heavy.test.
@               IN  NS    ns2.mail-heavy.test.
@               IN  A     203.0.113.10
@               IN  MX    10 mx1.mail-heavy.test.
@               IN  MX    20 mx2.mail-heavy.test.
@               IN  MX    50 mx-fallback.mail-heavy.test.
@               IN  TXT   "v=spf1 mx a:mail-heavy.test -all"
_dmarc          IN  TXT   "v=DMARC1; p=quarantine; rua=mailto:postmaster@mail-heavy.test"
default._domainkey IN TXT "v=DKIM1; k=rsa; p=MIGfMA0GCSqGSIb3DQEBAQUAA4GNADCBiQKBgQC1234567890fakekey"
mx1             IN  A     203.0.113.20
mx1             IN  AAAA  2001:db8:113::20
mx2             IN  A     203.0.113.21
mx-fallback     IN  A     203.0.113.99
ns1             IN  A     203.0.113.2
ns2             IN  A     203.0.113.3
www             IN  A     203.0.113.10
